radiographic_examinations.findings: The visualized lung bases demonstrate no acute abnormality, including no consolidation or effusion. There are no pulmonary nodules or masses identified. There is no pericardial effusion. The liver is normal in size, contour and attenuation. There is no intra- or extra-hepatic biliary ductal dilation. The gallbladder is unremarkable. There is no cholelithiasis. The spleen, pancreas, and adrenal glands are normal. Kidneys enhance symmetrically with symmetric contrast excretion. There are bilateral extrarenal pelves, without hydronephrosis. There is a single 7-mm hypodense lesion in the interpolar region of the right kidney, too small to characterize. There are no concerning renal mass lesions identified. The stomach, duodenum, and loops of small bowel are normal. There is no free fluid or free air in the abdomen. There is no mesenteric or retroperitoneal adenopathy. The aorta is normal in caliber, and major mesenteric vessels are patent. The superior mesenteric vein and portal vein are widely patent. The appendix appears normal but does not fill with contrast, and the appendiceal tip is dilated and fluid-filled, with mucosal hyperenhancement, measuring up to 10 mm. No adjacent fluid or free air. No evidence of abscess formation. The uterus is normal in size with a small amount of fluid in the endometrial cavity. There are no adnexal masses. Distal ureters and bladder are normal. No suspicious lytic or sclerotic osseous lesions identified.
